lastFragmentLoadingBefore

public static int lastFragmentLoadingBefore(java.util.List<java.lang.Integer> initialSeq,
                                            CodeSplitter2.FragmentPartitioningResult result,
                                            int numSps,
                                            int firstFragment,
                                            int... restFragments)
The same as lastFragmentLoadingBefore(int, int...), except that all of the parameters must be passed explicitly. The instance method should be preferred whenever a JProgram instance is available.

Parameters:
initialSeq - The initial split point sequence of the program
result - The fragment partitioning result, null if it hasn't be partitioned.
numSps - The number of split points in the program
firstFragment - The first fragment to consider
restFragments - The rest of the fragments to consider

generalizeTypes

public JReferenceType generalizeTypes(java.util.Collection<? extends JReferenceType> types)
Return a minimal upper bound of a set of types. That is, a type that is a supertype of all the input types and is as close as possible to the input types. NOTE: Ideally we would like to return the least upper bound but it does not exit as the Java type hierarchy is not really a lattice. Hence, this function depends on the collection order. E.g. I O |\ / \ | A B \ / \ / C where I is an interface an {O,A,B,C} are classes. generalizeTypes({A,C}) could either be I or O. In particular generalizeTypes({I,A,C}) = I and generalizeTypes({A,C,I}) = O.

generalizeTypes

public JReferenceType generalizeTypes(JReferenceType type1,
                                      JReferenceType type2)
Return the least upper bound of two types. That is, the smallest type that is a supertype of both types.
